Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
As part of an amendment to the criminal law, the Ukrainian parliament refused the proposed annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
On second reading, MEPs rejected the proposed amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko described the regime's ruling as political revenge and caused a process of suspicion of partiality in the court also to the west.
The plan to cancel paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
