The diet of an obese child: does not eat breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
Over a third of children aged 9-13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren have a weight above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being and the models around him are is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, 50% of the meat is found more frequently than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obeity is no coincidence"
In the families of the big ones sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most of today's schoolchildren - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and involved 900 students from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is no coincidence", an action supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever society.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the absence of a proper diet and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned say for example eat 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch - snack- dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet", says one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the student families eat at the same time.
In most families each has their own breakfast.
And the worst thing that has been noted is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are more often consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sport regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet based on their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating".
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is in particular a great preference for sweet lemonades", is indicated in the results of the survey.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
Children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Towards health
The survey also showed that children are prepared to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session "Obesity is not a coincidence", a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet was established," the results of the survey indicate.
For example, the most notable was for sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and knedliky (Czech speciality of bread flour or potato pellets).
