History of IBM: From cheese slices to the flights in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it originally had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then shaded the firm's founder - Watson's ideas have been the basis of society's identity and culture to date.
Watson was head of the Kusqu's firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, sales increased to $9 million and began to expand to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide the flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but purchased the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with advice and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM over the last three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and urban management.
As far as the business area is concerned, IBM recently developed a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps businessmen to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history on our territory as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 when it was the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, besides IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the research and development team at the global level that is responsible for the recognition of speech.
