How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination for the West and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however it was necessary to line up all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not tradable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The Czechs' travels have since experienced a great revolution.
Although vacations in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most until 1989, the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in neighbouring countries of the West has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not for a long time travel by plane to the west which everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example in Paris travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a boarding house.
The typical feature of a Czech trip at that time was to take with you its own preserved food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage increased, which caused another important moment around 1997.
As a result of increasing demand for travel travel travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter routes that through contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to rank completely in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time ever in history spent more than 15 000 kronor per person on holidays abroad including ancillary charges. Crowns per person.
