21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that moved
From Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell to ruin.
Now it is again open and is used as an exhibition house.
If we are excited for a modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, its glass hangars, its bright and bold appearances and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the universal exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its steel and glass construction, light and suspended.
Construction is considered to be an important step in contemporary architecture until today.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian universal exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His project of pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the southern railway station in Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become more and more dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "21st century house" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday night the Belvedere museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a lucky blow from any point of view.
The new start was completed by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian Belvedere gallery.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career, among other things in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she carried out the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments, she obtained public funds and private sponsorship and established the exploitation of them.
Except for contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name were exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are there, and an office must be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal performer.
Not only because he had transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht's secession with sensitivity and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had "practically seen every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his travel to Vienna and his change of use.
During the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was "a gulf of energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was placed and the roof was replaced by a particular safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a sifted light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in a shade protection against rust red-brown color.
And the cinema is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the close supervision of the authorities responsible for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and which also please the office of protection monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to raw soil in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City".
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands the newly planned "neighborhood of the central station" with offices and apartments.
And perhaps another lucky blow will happen: the 21st century house could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art centre, and as it says, it is already negotiating with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
