Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. Entitled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that embraces your heart.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page and make your mark-up.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic story of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fogs of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
Here he wrote an extraordinary book which he accurately describes as "an anti-history book."
It has some well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors or discussions on strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it could look like." It contains "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, go crazy or lose their lives.
Their lives roar here like the candles of a church: while some die, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
It contradicts the idea that the First World War can be summed up only by the terrible war of trenches on the western front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of corditeness.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you are a mother in the house, do you stay or run away?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, expectations, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them deal with deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz. "
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on alternative food in Germany.
It describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep's fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 authorized substitute meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
