The walls have eyes: researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy expressing his anti-immigration opinions online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having been caught of murderous madness in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, was confronted with his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, it was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, talking with some of the millions of nationalists who support extreme right-wing groups on social media sites.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how can we find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so difficult to find them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the website's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific precision - the way Merchantians have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of extreme right-wing groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
By coming into contact with these people thanks to Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and her colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"This is a new way of doing research," says Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young people and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen."
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through "I Love", publications on walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the "data supernova" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research projects whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to investigate people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter," says Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken exploits were far more likely to be alcoholic than students who were discreet about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as counsellors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Centre for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who in another case would not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied the statistics concerning the situation of love and Valentine's Day, the turnout in the mid-term elections of 2010 and a national happiness index (thanks to the information only available - the champions of digital freedom have long argued that the site could make its treasure of data available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined instructions on how to collect information other than via the Internet, it is quite another thing online.
"I don't think that many users have ever thought about a researcher being able to study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, based on a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As long as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things," says Selwyn.
This is why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and pen remain the best tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people," he says.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and social is not in front of a computer."
