Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, came to be an idiot by quickly issuing contradicted denials with irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of violations of campaign funding related to the coverage of an extramarital liaison.
And then, none of the people who have lived the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered while lying during his second term on his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers have given the students the answers to the tests in order to make themselves visible on their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceit do we meet?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, let's say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data gathered over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don't stutter, blush, or always agitate.
Not to conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerge from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, than men say more lies "centered on them" while women say more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you say if someone's lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "establishing benchmark data."
This helps to provide a baseline to measure future changes.
Observe your subject's posture, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves his feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him shaking his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for evidence of verbal and non-verbal deceptive behaviour.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
The interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is finished just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson skipped using the past while pretending that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a distanced language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a very difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember correctly... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances for anyone to avoid victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
