In the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, unemployment and informality in Sinaloa increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year to be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations with regard to the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in return there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing trillion dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction in economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly due to the historical drop of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development's report of frost allocations, there was damage to 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the state's unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year there was an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 000 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate which represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of the year of 18 000 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money-laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to win them, to invest them and use them in something," he says.
Migration in custody
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to work abroad in the United States has been reduced, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which means that unemployment is rising," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market worsens by considering the high level of lack of seriousness which predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for lag for the state are low wages, the entity has the lower wages of the Country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly earnings of Sinaloan workers were, until September, 5 000 352 pesos, well below the national average, which is 7 000 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction of the Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State FDI reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by the companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State requested in July at the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reviving the economy, the approval of the state congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no debt benefits were observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrates a lack of management capacity in the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonisation of the wishes of the various sectors, here included the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year was really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, it has had to align everyone's effort and especially the already synchronized good progress of this new government team, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts of the beginning of the year have retained the state economy and restricted its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced by several events, between which the frosts, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close far below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation Patronale of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources be removed," he says.
Much to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better channel the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to achieve good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programma," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
