Court validates "the analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies had formulated against the presidential decree which put forward the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it were not gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to achieve the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic has been rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is an assignment reserved by law to the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favour of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero even.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and admit the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also decided to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the minister president said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure the measures for the public administration to prepare for it through general standards.
"I also consider that if it does so it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has as its constitutional mandate the direction of the State.
The substitution of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years and this translates into better exploitation of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalisation, which implies a decision in the public interest that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "requires the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the State, includes a group of attributions which the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in a form the sphere of competence of Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he said.
Analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve either its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process could come into force, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for by the Law of the State Gazette, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9th November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and characterized as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state's agent for constitutional reforms, because it does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to make the partial and total counting of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no minutes of voting and there are no counts in the ballot box file; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged winner of the respective election and the candidate who obtained the second place in the election is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition who presented the second of the candidates indicated.
The total counting of the vote may also be carried out if at the end of the common counting it follows that the difference between the supposed winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party whose candidate came out second, in which case the electoral packages which were subject to the partial counting shall be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
