Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal and this one will be released
After 72 days of provisional arrest, the legal authority of Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the Mayor of Monterrey for the trial initiated against him for alleged blackmails
After 72 years of arrest, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the founder of the legal power of Casino Red grants him pardon before the Second Criminal Court of the District, which follows a trial for blackmail against the brother of the Mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded payment of an economic quartet for the mayor of Monterrey to allow the underground operation of the gambling house.
After the public denunciation, the Public Prosecutor's Office opened a criminal trial against the brother of the mayor, and on 2 September he was arrested and held under provisional arrest for 30 days.
After four hours in front of the Public Prosecutor's Office 3 of Patriotic Crimes, he was transferred to Detention Centre 1, located in the Old District of the State Capital.
He remained there for the following 49 days when he was issued a second detention order after the Public Prosecutor's Office dismissed the offences of corruption and organized crime.
On the 19th of October he was transferred to the penal center of Cadereyta allegedly for having blackmailed the owners of Casino Red with a million and a half pesos; but he spent only a few hours in the medium security detention centre because there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On 25 October, an order of capture was issued by the clerk of the Second Criminal Court of the District, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigation there was sufficient confirmed evidence to determine Jonás' guilt, such as that relating to the collection of 1.5 million pesos of the representatives of the gambling house in exchange for allowing it to operate.
This Monday, the founder of the legal power of the Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, appeared before Judge José Luis Pecina to seek forgiveness for the brother of the mayor of the region; therefore he could recover his freedom in the following hours.
During the legal proceedings, the Public Prosecutor's Office official attached to the Tribunal, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez whether the damage had been recovered and who of the members of the gambling house had been the one who granted the pardon, but the lawyer tried not to disclose the name.
According to case 197/2011 the legal pardon is granted to Jonás Larrazábal and later no claim can be made regarding the trial against him; he will not be asked for any compensation for the damage nor any punishment.
After the hearing of the lawyer of the legal power of the gambling house, at 15:50 hours the immediate freedom of Larrazabal Bretón was ordered.
The Registrar of the Tribunal, Jorge Yánez, travelled to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been forgiven legally and his file would be closed.
He will also communicate to him the order of immediate freedom issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air accident in which the government secretary, Francisco Blake and other seven people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) informed that the results of the accident in which government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven others lost their lives indicate that the helicopter shocked directly against the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to try a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that investigations in the impact area did not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search it was reported that there were no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact occurred structurally.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The soil had a seven- to 30-degree slope.
For the time being, the secretary has assured us that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, managing director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that the moment of impact, the Major Presidential State helicopter was operating in speed of cruiser and it happened on a soft rising ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruising operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, the SCT holder, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical norm, the flight was conducted according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM indicated adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced towards the boundary area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-level layers of nebulosity.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the nebulosity conditions the crew sought a lower height area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact has occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft's residual dispersion model suggests that the helicopter struck the ground under structural integrity conditions.
Traces of fire or explosion have not been detected:
In the area of the disaster there is still no trace in the remnants of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,800,200 feet above the average sea level, and the ground had a slope that has been going down from seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides evidence that suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the surrounding area around the accident, dispersal parts of the aircraft were not found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and youth, called the protocol 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation it is invited to participate the population entitled or not, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the proofs to minors take place every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He pointed out that the protocol started in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sporting Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independence Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and the objective of knowing the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and youth to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, to apply the specific questionnaires on nutrition.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that, on Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin, and genetics (i.e., identification of people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 per cent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 per cent; in the case of overweight, there was also a dramatic increase," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others in its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American inheritance, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the full assessment of children, which allows us to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-coloured folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and the physicians provide it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pâté with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintaining the oil pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture having characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, of nearly 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involved asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones forming the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles pass there by generating effort, it allows forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, opined chemical engineering.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the effort, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material made of it must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because these greatly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, the water pours out inside the layer is difficult for the layer to get out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that gets ruined is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, in order to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
