Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali typist passed to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
The past 4 November a typist from the Cali ITC has passed to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists working in the local ITC offices, this week it was the "availability" tour of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipes of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the corpses that had to be identified were located.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was running the world's oldest guardilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the dead body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a collector and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farc.
Looking for the fingerprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our job.
Typing is an exact science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying the corpses, the typists support the investigation of offences such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the persons captured.
When captured, many offenders have false IDs or no documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher said that in one case of theft he had to remove a part of a wall from a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the entire handprint and identify the offender who had participated in various thefts," he recalls.
The fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently, we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Interluded with the investigation, it was determined that a parent could be a suspect of the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him at the crime scene.
An ITC typist explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents are extracted".
When they appear, a collector or tape is used to collect them.
Later, fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the expert of the ITC.
He explained that not everything is how one shows in the CSI television program.
As all that shines is not gold, all that one touches does not necessarily become a print.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indignant" defy the authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators were scrambling in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large part of the people accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities this Tuesday by trying to enter again, through a judicial order, instead of Manhattan, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park in the Grande Apple.
Hundreds of demonstrators were jostling in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a judicial order that allowed the 'indignant' to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp in the square again, we will settle in another place and we will continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," said one of the spokespersons of the "Occupy Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the 'indignant' response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the site and allowed the demonstrators to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignant' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church Parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some demonstrators, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, making sure Efe saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are centenarians of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved as a sign of support to the members of the movement and tried to intervene for them in front of the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a private property enclosure - remains closed pending the celebration of a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of the evacuation of this morning is to be analysed.
Some of the displaced demonstrators were carrying and distributing copies of the court order at that time, and they even handed it over to the officers who were monitoring the square, which caused 'some small clashes', Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials hit the demonstrators.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evacuating the members of Occupy Wall Street or from applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or from prohibiting demonstrators from returning to the park with tents or other properties that they previously used'.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, as a result of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and demonstrators, but warned them that local laws did not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The municipal councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the demonstrators were "in violation of the law".
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place in which people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to harm others", because "some stores had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"The evacuation from this morning to dawn has been repugnant and shows that at the bottom Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of the American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression".
The officials of "Occupy Wall Street" also said that they do not think to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with the community organisations and the unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on 17 September.
