Japan Reborn after the Earthquake
GDP increases 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy was paralyzed, recovering again after the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government have calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow which, despite the difficult global context, seems to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and a 6% at annualized rates.
That recorded in the second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase since January to March 2010.
Part of the recovery is due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decrease in 0.9% of capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructures, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased 1%, driven by increased expenditures on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo recovered to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refusal values" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in Eurozone and the forecast turmoil of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September for the yen's contribution.
While markets continue to have their seats in the EU's peripheral countries, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lose its guard.
"We must follow the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the points of inflection of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being restrained.
As it dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in level 100, dropping eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
Athens feeds doubts again
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With the peripheral risk premiums triggered and the uncertainty resettled in the parks, Greece continues to become entangled in the maze that leads to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek Transitional Government is imposed rather by the Brussels demands than by a real conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos yesterday reported that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the period of one hundred days established in his designation will perhaps be short to apply them, the leader of the Conservative New Democracy Party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the scheduled date of 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the 26 October summit," declared Papadimos when he opened yesterday a parliamentary debate that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to stimulate employment, reform of the civil servants' disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras no's message raises doubts about his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the Transitional Government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything more".
The conservative leader has gone one step further in his pulse than EU and IMF, the agencies that need to release the 8,000 million Athens urgently needs, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to implement the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the whole of the Papandreu referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock the aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
The Spokesman for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new government "the elements necessary to pay the sixth instalment" of 8,000 million, even if there is no final date either.
