Queen Sofía: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen emphasises Spain's "preponderant" position with regard to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a prominent place at the global level in the role of Microfinance".
Queen Sofía recalled that in the last two decades the country has become the second donor of the planet with regard to this instrument of cooperation whose "essential" lies in the fact that it is a "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the V World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" in order to achieve the Millennium Goals established by the United Nations for 2015, and "very especially in the one that aims to reduce to half the volume of people living on incomes under one dollar a day, to which is set the "poverty threshold".
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in all parts of the world, and takes on this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions from the Summit, which will last until Thursday, "ensure the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved many goals" and "we face many challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is envisaged not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to push "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that by the end of 2015 there were 175 million poor families who had access to these financial services and that one hundred million of these families would come out of the poverty line in which they now live.
The impetus in the design of microcredits in Spain and in the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, stressed Queen Sofía as a "act of justice and due recognition".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", the work that she has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to know her lending policy on the ground.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those celebrated in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "at each meeting I was able to see a continuous evolution", explained Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought her yesterday the term "head of the family" gathered in Valladolid from the "banker of the poor".
Finally, Queen Sofía finished her speech by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to advance in the fight against poverty.
"Ethic imperative"
The Minister for External Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In this sense, she explained that it would be a mistake to vinculate cooperation with developing countries at times of economic prosperity, as it is a "permanent obligation".
Jiménez considered that microcredits presuppose "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of the developed countries must work under criteria of solidarity and not let it be the victim of the cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "trust" to the "excluded" people to whom everyone closes the door; and the Mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed those present in a city that "opens its doors contaminated with the spirit of solidarity".
