First of all with a view to budgetary savings: the government intends to impose on private employees a fourth day of deficiency before taking over a work stoppage.
In short, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' pay, thus at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could cause anger, but which would bring back 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And which would be accompanied by another measure, of a more symbolic scope: to impose on officials a day of non-indemnification in the event of a work stoppage (they have so far no waiting period, compared with three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also revives the topic of fraud, this time targeting the abuse of work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, in addition, if you are taken, you will pay back," Xavier Bertrand told RTL's microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the publicity effects appear somewhat disproportionate with the reality of fraud at work stoppages.
It has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no more ill than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us focus first on the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million in daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, with EUR 11.3 billion.
Of this amount, 46% were for maternity and work-related accidents, and 54% were for sick leave, or €6.2 billion.
And so 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French had an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting Group.
An average that hides some discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the Monster.com career management site, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any day of sick leave.
Another study, this time from Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared to their European neighbours, French employees are no more inclined than elsewhere to work stoppages.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) ranged from 10% to 11% in France, compared with 20% to 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud at sick leave represents very little in the face of work in the dark.
