In the case of systematically controlled stops of more than 45 days, 11% of the 1.2 million cases were "inadequate or unjustified", or 132,000.
In total, 169,000 "unjustified" cases out of several million employees who have had a stoppage of illness.
A figure which is very little in comparison, for example, with the figure of black work.
According to MP UMP Dominique Tian, who wrote a report on the issue in June, it would amount to €9 to €15 billion in tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud to them.
Papadémos: Greece will have to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to redress its economy.
This is what Prime Minister Lucas Papadémos said before Parliament on Monday 14 November, adding that the 100 days given to his union government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"In order to continue efforts to recover the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new fiscal adjustment programme," said the head of government, who gave his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, as the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake", he added.
As a result, Mr Papadémos has planned that the country's public deficit will be reduced "around 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after having been 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
