Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says a committee of experts.
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the committee called for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctors about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements for that purpose.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, with the participation of six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts quote a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medically or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, reports experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire that most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, this rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where such approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization results in abuse of the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on persons who are not competent or consenting.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, said yesterday in teleconference, there would be more cases of such excesses in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assistant suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in Support of Euthanasia
It should be noted that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
As for persons who have committed assisted suicide, the respondents estimate that they should not be prosecuted at 41%.
The situation with regard to the maintenance or termination of patient care is less clear, the authors of the report say.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that withdrawal from care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In the area of palliative care, the committee called for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health care institutions, the Committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to terminally ill patients.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also pointed out that the authors of the report seemed to place the autonomy of the person above all the other values that participated in the social fabric of society.
Now, "in society," he says, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the conclusions of the report, which she described as "pro-euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, disputes in particular the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely in the Netherlands and Oregon.
