On Tuesday, the government of the great social-democratic-Christian coalition in power in Austria decided to include in the constitution a "golden rule" budget in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible deterioration by the rating agencies of the sovereign note of Austria (triple A).
The Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the 60% maximum criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
