Energy policy:
the facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is a subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy for an election to be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear power.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will result in a doubling of the demand for electricity by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be overcome in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only new generation plants.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, the Czech Republic, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its fleet by taking over the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
While the German renewable energy model is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, in particular from Russia, a rise in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated.
He is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittentness of the wind, with 30% of his electricity, and 65% and 50% higher than the European average respectively.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than those of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the fine declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show any opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show this.
Let us recall that our country's energy policy has built an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410 000 jobs.
Strongly exporting, it brings a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very much creating non-relocable jobs.
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros per year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity generation, nor is there any evil one.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a safety authority that exercises intransigence and transparency over existing power plants as well as on the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions and remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did with the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wishing to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the clear way to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the number policy, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights countries" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has come to light, with the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, fear of the invasion of national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as well as on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be paid for by election; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and harming employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants may replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, with downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly engaged in trades in sectors in need of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average at 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenues less expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average throughout his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term of office, to look for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, by being used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, Europe still has to think about democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember it, which, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to definitively triumph over its enemies to exercise the vote and exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even be made "an instrument of oppression" as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, first and foremost, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have had in this respect the value of double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought out in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now moved, and for many of them Republican soldiers no longer shoot in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to necessity and in dispersed order.
A white-seing to the absolute European monarch or a foot jump joined in the vacuum of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cutlets, but a common exercise, of course, serene and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - and there is no longer any way to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that lies with the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are worried about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the management of the European project.
For it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without complete democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long fight against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
All right.
But thinking it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take a new step in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
