Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Long-suspected, the links between the Al-Qaida terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram continue.
On Sunday, Algeria's Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Algiers has now "acquis la certitude".
"The way in which the two organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that there is good cooperation," he explained without further detail.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January is said to have uncovered bridges.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators had to find several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of past calls is directed to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has spent a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram and the other to a man who claims to be close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward but we must probably wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram".
"But it's possible."
"It has been known for years that the sect has received external financial and intellectual support and is becoming increasingly active," said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" had been increasingly evident in Boko Haram's evolution and discourses or in his operating procedures, which now involve the use of more and more complex suicide bombers or explosive devices and on the same basis as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, beginning with Washington, has therefore pressured Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illumines of little interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, school and fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which in Haousa means "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is rapidly successful.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for the sharia while its militants engage in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are aimed primarily at churches, bars and administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, multiplying attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army is investing the city. There are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on the sect will radicalize and leave its fiefs from the north.
Last Christmas, she claims an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the police's secure headquarters during a suicide attack, his first.
In August, the UN headquarters will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would navigate from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria now worries all security professionals.
While Aqmi has invested Mali and Niger, while al-Shebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears to be a new threat at the heart of the continent.
Last week, during an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all the information".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete for simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the others have multiplied the tone of statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsubstantiated - sound.
Mitt Romney, the best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese to the WTO and question them "for manipulation of their currency", a theme that was a source of frustration in an America that was driven by the migration of entire sections of its industry to Asia.
So much if it should involve the outbreak of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama's former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, almost strangled himself against an attitude that "flavors" emotions.
He called for a strong but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama's current position).
But Huntsman, who stagnates in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Like Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
"If I'm elected, I'll stop Iran," he bragging.
"If Obama is re-elected, they'll have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, shows an embarrassing lack of knowledge of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing "trying to develop a nuclear capability" - apparently unaware of the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texan Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to hire the US army in Mexico against the drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
The opponents of the current president replied that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he had won the cold war.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine with regard to anti-terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq, on his procrastination in Libya, thus sticking to him a weak label.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population is quite positive about Obama's national security record, which eliminated Bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to stalemate.
And, arguing that America needs to be economically rebuilt to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more justly.
The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brilliantly.
More than 500 guests including four Heads of State and Government took part on the Baltic coast last Tuesday, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline which directly connects Russia with Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Land.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, which will deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say, the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a breach between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to overcome its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming and whose deposits are declining.
" This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically, " confirmed François Fillon in opening this gas pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, many present in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from anchors from ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
There has also been a need to increase measures to protect wildlife.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers gave up while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company established permanently off their coasts.
" In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute, " says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds for leakage every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft operating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one metre wide, and it is pushed by gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, it provides precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at departure, and 100 at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported, " says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided at 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to go back to their costs, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas arriving before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskin, a bookmark.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, Moleskin wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of an off-white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has restored to the taste of the light an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crossed Italian borders and exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw up a sketch of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskin, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early days, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from La Fnac to small shops in the city centre and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the look of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies Moleskine's development: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a wide range of supports.
A success that has made envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Disturbing?
" No, " says Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
" The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable. "
" At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. "
" Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done. "
It must be said that for the disabled unemployed, there are still many obstacles before they reach employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, all these criteria make it particularly difficult to return to employment, and which are "the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Springboard, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
It remains the unsaid, the evolving mentality, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "over-representation of persons in wheelchairs, persons with mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from meeting the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, dating back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
" We are now around 3%, " says Pierre Blanc, General Manager of the Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, " explains Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
